So far, the solar cell has been described by a general blackbody. Now we will assume that the solar cell is described by a single-junction solar cell, which consists of a semiconductor with a constant bandgap. The ultimate conversion efficiency represents a theoretical energy conversion efficiency limit of a semiconductor-based solar cell. Photons with photon energies larger than or equal to the bandgap are absorbed. Photons with energies smaller than the bandgap are not absorbed. It is assumed that photogenerated electron/hole pairs are collected. Recombination of electron/hole pairs is not considered. Only thermalization and absorption losses are considered. Absorption losses occur for photon energies smaller than the bandgap and thermalization losses occur for energies larger than the bandgap [41]. The photon flux of the sun, which is absorbed by the solar cell, is given by Eq. 16 [5, 41]:16FCellT=TSun=2πh3c2∫Eg∞E2dEexpEkTSun-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
